# Keyboard Keys in Linux 

Arrow Keys: Navigate through text, commands, and menus
Home/End: Move the cursor to the beginning/end of a line
Page Up/Page Down: Scroll through pages of content
Ctrl + C: Copy selected text or terminate a running process in the terminal
Ctrl + V: Paste copied text
Ctrl + X: Cut selected text
Ctrl + Z: Undo the last action
Ctrl + A: Select all 

Terminal-Specific Shortcuts:
Ctrl + Alt + T: Open a new terminal window.
Ctrl + Shift + T: Open a new tab within the current terminal window.
Ctrl + Shift + V: Paste into the terminal.
Ctrl + L: Clear the terminal screen.
Ctrl + U: Cut everything to the left of the cursor.
Ctrl + K: Cut everything to the right of the cursor.
Ctrl + R: Search through command history.
  
System and Desktop Control:
Alt + F4: Close the current window.
Alt + Tab: Switch between open applications.
Ctrl + Alt + Del: Often used to bring up a system menu for shutdown/reboot options or to access the task manager.
Super key (Windows key): Opens the application launcher or activities overview in many desktop environments.
Ctrl + Alt + F1-F6: Switch to virtual consoles (text-based terminals).
Ctrl + Alt + F7: Switch back to the graphical desktop environment.
Ctrl + Alt + L: Lock the screen


