# File System Linux :
File system is used by the operating system to manage files. The system controls how data is saved and retrived.
Operating system stores files and directory in structured and organized manner.
Linux uses ext3,ext4,xfs file system.

File System Structure:
1. /boot : This file contains boot loader files ie grub.cfg this load everytime when the os is powerd up.
           this the first thing which load when the system is powerd up
2. /root : This is the root users home directory.Its not same as /
3. /dev  : System devices infomation is stored here like disk,rom,flashdrive,keyboard etc
4. /etc  : all system configuration files are stored here 
           User and Group Management: Files like /etc/passwd, /etc/shadow, and /etc/group manage user accounts, passwords, and group memberships.
           Network Configuration: Files in /etc/sysconfig/network-scripts (for older systems) or managed by NetworkManager control network interfaces, 
		   IP addresses, and routing.
           Service Configuration: Files within /etc/systemd/system or /etc/init.d (for older systems) configure how services start, stop, and behave.
           Boot Settings: Files like /etc/fstab define how file systems are mounted during boot, and GRUB configuration files control the boot loader.
           Application Settings: Many applications store their global configuration settings within subdirectories of /etc, such as /etc/ssh for SSH server 
		   settings or /etc/cups for CUPS printer settings. 
5. /bin  : everyday use cmds are stored here           or cd /usr/bin
6. /sbin : system configuration cmds are stored here   or cd /usr/sbin 
7. /opt  : this folder store optional or third party file data ex.oracal , SAP etc 
8. /proc : Its shows the services runing in the memory / live services 

