# Acess Control List :
  ACL provides additional, more flexible permission machanism for file system.
  Its desgined to assist with UNIX/LINUX file system.
  ACL allows you to give file permission to any user, group to any file, directory or disk space.
  
  *Use of ACL:
  Think of a scenario in which user is not a member of a group created by you , but still you want to give read and write acess to that user
  So,you can give that user a read/write permission to that user without adding inside the group an this can done using the ACL.
  
  *cmd used 
  1.setfacl : To give acess permission to user/group 
  2.getfacl : To display information about the file
  
  1.To add permission for a user:
  ~]# setfacl -m u:username:rwx /path/path/path 
      -m : modify
       u : user 
      rwx: permissions you want to provide 
  2.TO add permission to group :
  ~]# setfacl -m g:<groupname>:rwx /path/path
      g : group 
  3.To allow all files and directories to inherit ACl from the diectory it is with in / from main directory 
  ~]# setfacl -dm "entry" /path/to/dir 
  4.To remove all permissions from specific user 
  ~]# setfacl -x u:<username> /path/to/file 
  5.To remove permissions from all users 
  ~]# setfacl -b /path/to/file 
  6. To get details of ACL 
  ~]# getfacl /path/to/file 
  
  If you add ACL permission to any file/folder then it will add + sign at the end of permissions.
  Setting 'w' permission to file will not allow you to delete/remove the file.

