# Input - Output Redirect 
Everything in the linux (file,directory,logs,devices etc) are consider as a file.
When processor open any file then kernal gives number to this process called File Discriptor Number. ie 0,1,2 etc 
A file diecriptor is a index into a preprocess table that keeeps track of the all open files.
It allow process to read, write and manipulate file.
    		
	# There are 3 redirect in linux
    1.stdin : standard input (stdin) have file discriptor as 0 
    2.stdout: standard output have file discriptor as 1 
    3.stderr: standard error have file discriptor as 2 

A.stdout : 
By default when ruuning a cmd the output will go to the terminal.
If you want to route the op of cmd to the file then you run cmd :-   (previous_cmd) > (file_name) ex- ls -ltr > file1.txt 
If you want to route the op of cmd to the file without overwriting or for append use :- prv_cmd >> file_name.txt 

B.When a command is executed we use a keyboard and that is considerd as a stdin-0 
ex- cat < test.txt 

C.stderr-2 
When a cmd is execute we use a keyboard and that is considerd as a stdin-0 
That cmd output goes to the terminal/monitor and op is stdout-1 
If cmd produced any error on the screen then its considerd as a stderr-2 
   we can use redirects to route error from screen 
    ex- ~]# telnet localhost
        ~]# trying to connect...
            telnet:unable to connect to remote host:connection refused.
        ~]# telnet localhost 2 > errorfile.txt {This will append error msg to the txt file} 
		~]# cat errorfile.txt 
		~] telnet:unable to connect to remote host:connection refused.
		
