# Special Permissions : setuid , setgid , sticky bit 
1. setuid :
         When the file with the setuid executes, it run with the permissions of the file owner ,
		 and not user running the files.
		 Commonly used for the tasks which requird elevated privillages.
		 Commonly used for the tasks which requird elevated privillages.
		 -rwsr-xr-x  : 's' provides the special permission to the user 
        Ex- chk if passwd uses setuid :
        ~]# ls -l /usr/bin/passwd 
        ~] -rwsr-xr-x 1 root root 54256 sep1 2025 /usr/bin/passwd 
	cmd : chmod u+s <filename> 
        ~]# chmod u+s file1.txt 
 
    * To remove special permission: 
    cmd : chmod u-s <filename> 
	
2. setgid :
         For files : runs with the permissions of group owner.
         For Directories : new files created will inherit the group ownership from the directory rather 
		 than the users 
		 defualt group.
		   to add permission :
            ~]# chmod g+s <file>
            to remove permission :
            ~]# chmod g-s <file> 
		 
3. sticky bit : 
             This allow only owner of the file or root to delete the file. Normal users cant delete or 
			 rename files with sticky bit ie 't' extension.
			 Commonly used to directories like /tmp to prevent usrs from deleting others files.
			cmd : 
			~]# chmod +t <file> 
			To remove :
			cmd :
			~]# chmod -t <file>
*** To find all executables which have setuid or setgid permission we can use cmd :
    ~]# find /-perm / 6000 -type f 



