# SSH : secure shell
shell takes commands from the user or OS and takes that commands to kernal.
its the CLI based interface.

SSh is itself secure,
SSH communication is always encrypted.
Following are some additional configurations of the SSH :
A. Add time interval 
-> Become root 
~]# su - 
-> Edit your /etc/ssh/sshd_config file and add following file 
~]# vi /etc/ssh/sshd_config 
~] clientAliveInternal 600 
   clientAliveCountMax 0
~]# systemctl restart sshd 

  sshd is the daemon. 
  The idle timeout interval you are setting is in seconds [ 600 seconds = 10 min ] after 10 mins the idle user will be automatically logged out.   

B. Disable root login :
   It will disable any other user to log in as a root user.
-> Become root 
~]# su - 
-> Edit /etc/ssh/sshd_config file and replace PermitRootLogin yes to no
~]# vi /etc/ssh/sshd_config 
~] PermitRootLogin no 
~]# systemctl restart sshd 

C. Disable Empty passwords 
   You need to prevent logins from account with empty passsword for added security.
   
~]# su - 
~]# vi /etc/ssh/sshd_config 
~] ...
   PermitEmptyPasswords no    [Remove #]
~]# systemctl restart sshd    
   
D. Limit users SSH acess :
   To provide another layer of security, you should limit your SSH logins to only certain users who need remote acess. 
~]# su -
~]# vi /etc/ssh/sshd_config
~] ...
   AllowUsers user1 user2 
~]# systemctl restart sshd

E. Use differnat port :
  Normally ssh is running on port 22. you can chnage that port for added security.

